article.description:
Caron Butler scored 22 points and fellow 
rookie Rasual Butler added 18 as the Miami Heat snapped a
six-game home losing streak with a 107-98 victory over the
Toronto Raptors.
article.headline: Heat win for just 14th time at home this season
article.linkText: Heat win for just 14th time at home this season
article.story:
MIAMI (AP) -- The Miami Heat pulled out a rare home victory. Rookie Caron Butler scored 22 points and the Heat snapped a four-game losing streak with a 107-98 victory over the Toronto Raptors on Friday night. Rasual Butler scored 18 points for Miami, and Brian Grant added 12 points and 10 rebounds as the Heat snapped a six-game losing streak at home and scored 100 points for just the eighth time. Miami's win was just its 14th at home, and its first since March 2. "Of all the things that have gone wrong this year, the inability to be at least .500 at home or to be more consistent has been the most disappointing,'' Heat coach Pat Riley said. "Somewhere along the way, we have to try to get back the home court advantage. This building has not been one that has been intimidating to anyone. It used to be, we'd always win 30-33 games at home, but it has been very difficult lately.'' The Heat got a season-high 53 points from their reserves, including 18 from Malik Allen and 11 from Sean Lampley in Miami's second win in 10 games. "Whoever came in kept the aggression going,'' Allen said. "Everybody contributed. We had a lot of energy off the bench. Everyone was really into this game, and that was nice to see.'' Caron Butler, who has led the Heat in scoring in five of the last seven games, notched his third straight game with 20 or more points. Vince Carter scored 30 points, and Alvin Williams added 15 points and seven assists for the Raptors, who have lost seven of eight and six straight on the road. "We're trying to play everybody and make substitutions,'' Raptors coach Lenny Wilkens said. "From a defensive standpoint, in the second quarter, we did not get back. We never recovered from that. Overall, we didn't play badly, but when you put yourself in a hole, it's difficult to get out.'' Trailing by 19 in the fourth, Toronto closed within five on Carter's 3-pointer that made it 99-94. A charging call against Chris Jefferies with just under two minutes left halted the rally. "It just killed our whole momentum,'' Jefferies said. "I think we were on a surge and could have cut the lead to two or three. I was hitting, and Vince was just destroying, but as soon as (they) called that charge, it seemed like everything just stopped.'' Rasual Butler hit a jumper, then a 3-pointer to put the Heat up 104-94 with 1:01 left. Miami led 80-70 entering the fourth and extended its lead to 89-72 in the first three minutes. Following a technical foul against Voshon Lenard, Miami's Travis Best and Lampley combined to make three free throws, and Allen made a jumper to open a 19-point lead.

Game notes
Raptors forward Antonio Davis, who suffered a bruised right knee in the second half Wednesday against the Hawks, wasn't in uniform for the game. ... Heat guard Mike James aggravated his ribs in the first half and sat out the rest of the game. ... The game featured the NBA's two winningest coaches, although both are struggling through hard times this season. Wilkens leads NBA coaches with 1,289 wins and Riley is second with 1,107. ... Carter has led the Raptors in scoring in nine of the last 10 games. ... Mamadou N'diaye started for just the fourth time for the Raptors, while the Heat's Vladimir Stepania started for only the third time. ... Heat rookie Ken Johnson, playing in his sixth game of the year, scored his first four points of the season.
